This moving middle grade is for anyone who has ever asked themselves: How do you figure out where you are going if you don’t know where you came from? Tap the link in bio to join in on behind-the-scenes chats and bonus content!

All I want for Christmas is…THE CHRISTMAS PRINCESS by the ✨one and only✨ Mariah Carey and Michaela Angela Davis; Illustrated by Fuuji Takashi! There's something about December that just makes us want to cozy up with a stack of good books! 📚⁠
⁠

We're continuing our 12 Days of Picture Books Countdown!⁠

THE CHRISTMAS PRINCESS follows Little Mariah and her journey to make this holiday season special by discovering the healing power of her voice and uses it to bring joy across the world. The northern lights dance,⁠
snow blankets the ground,⁠
it’s the Christmas season—so the Book Flood begins!⁠
⁠
People plan and they dream,⁠
and they visit the shops⁠
for books to give loved ones, and families, and friends.⁠
⁠
And when Christmas Eve comes,⁠
they’ll share magical stories,⁠
curl up by the fire, and read, read, read, read…⁠
⁠
A lovely and lyrical picture book, based on a real Icelandic tradition, THE CHRISTMAS BOOK FLOOD brings all the sparkle and anticipation of Christmas—and of the joys of reading—to the page.⁠
⁠
Grab your copy at the link in our bio! ⁠
⁠
📸 credit: @curlsupwithagoodbook⁠

What's your favorite holiday tradition?

 As the civil rights movement unfolds in Selma, Alabama, everyday life continues for the Brown family. In this collection of stories, Willie Mae Brown gives readers a personal insight into her coming of age in a town at the crossroads of history.

Make 2023 a year of exploration, learning and trying new things! 🖍️✂️⁠

It's time to start your ULTIMATE year of games with 365 Days of Play! This go-to activity book includes an activity for every day of the year. An encyclopedia of play, it's everything you need to keep little minds and hands entertained--pages on pages of games, crafts, recipes, experiments, projects, jokes, songs, guides, skills, tricks, hacks, challenges, and everything else in the canon of kid. Follow the step-by-step instructions and illustrations to create a game wherever you are and with whatever you have--swing a pendulum, launch a parachute, shoot a confetti cannon, or throw a boomerang. The hardcover book looks stunning on the shelf, toy chest, and coffee table, but will be well-loved by kids everywhere.

At the height of the civil rights movement in 1965, Willie Mae Brown was a young girl growing up in Selma, Alabama. 

Combining family stories of the everyday and the extraordinary as seen through the eyes of her twelve-year-old self, Willie Mae Brown's MY SELMA captures the voice and vision of a fascinating young person—perspicacious, impetuous, resourceful, and even mystical in her ways of seeing the world around her—who gifts us with a loving portrayal of her hometown while also delivering a no-holds-barred indictment of the time and place.

When she finds a feather, Grandma Dot adds it to her collection. Feathers, she tells her two granddaughters, remind Grandma Dot of people she’s lost. At first, the girls see the feathers as fun to play with. But soon, Grandma Dot’s feathers take on larger meanings – of comfort, remembrance, and love.⁠

Out now, Ken Schept and @rominaillustrations' A GIFT OF FEATHERS is an affectionate, hopeful story will inspire readers of all ages to make memories and traditions part of their own family stories.

"Dr. Martin Luther King Jr. walked slowly across the dais, took his position on the pulpit, and, looking out on the crowd, raised two palms. The people sat down and became quiet. Only the rustling of fabric on the church benches and the shuffling of shoes could be heard. 

Then Dr. King began to speak, and the voice and the words were not on the TV or radio. I was in front of him, and my mother was there. I heard him say: “We have the right to vote. Just give us the ballot.” So surreal was his voice, which mesmerized me, and the charisma of the time, with the unfolding of events and this giant of a man stepping forward to bring justice at any cost to the people, hypnotized me. 

I grew limp and trembled under the sound of his voice. His voice was like a dream, a dream that I dreamt each day while listening to the radio. Mama grabbed hold of me and rocked me back and forth as she listened to his words. My head lay in her chest and I could hear her heart beating fast as her tears fell from her eyes and into my hair."

Estelle Nadel⁣
1934 - 2023⁣
⁣
We were saddened to learn of the passing of Estelle Nadel, author of the forthcoming graphic novel, The Girl Who Sang.⁣
⁣
Born to a Jewish family in a small Polish village, Estelle Nadel—then known as Enia Feld—was just seven years old when the Nazis invaded Poland in 1939. Estelle was a vibrant child with a song for every occasion. ⁣
⁣
The Girl Who Sang is a first-hand account of Estelle's fight for survival during World War II. She would weather loss, betrayal, and spend two years away from the warmth of the sun—all before the age of eleven. And once the war was over, Estelle would walk barefoot across European borders and find remnants of home in an Austrian displaced persons camp before finally crossing the Atlantic to arrive in New York City.⁣
⁣
While we are heartbroken over Estelle's passing, we are proud that she got to hold this book in her hands, and that her story, one of a young girl's fight for survival and finding her voice, will be there for future generations of readers to keep her memory alive.
